Assignment 1 - Map and count¶

Biancamaria Florenzi, r0777934

Reference literature: Ma, H., Cao, L., Wang, F., Cheng, C., Jiang, R., Zhou, H., Xie, Z., Wuermanbieke, S., Qian, Z."Filamin B extensively regulates transcription and alternative splicing, and is associated with apoptosis in HeLa cells". Oncology Reports 43, no. 5 (2020): 1536-1546. https://doi.org/10.3892/or.2020.7532

Filamin B is an actin binding protein (ABP); in the study, RNA sequencing was used to analyse changes in the overall transcription between two conditions: HeLa control cells, and Filamin B knocked-down cells. Experimentally, it was previously shown that low expression levels of Filamin B are correlated with low cellular apoptosis; the hypothesis is that Filamin B regulates the expression of genes involved in cell appoptosis, tumor genesis and metastases in cancer cells.

Retrieving the fastq files from SRA¶

The sample related to the experiment are found at the following link: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sra/?term=srp216203 There are four samples, two for each conditions. The platform used is Illumina HiSeqXTen, the reads are 150 long and the spots are around 40 thousands for each sample, which should be high enough. The layout is paired and indeed we dump the files using the --split-files option.

I then renamed the files to FLNB and ctrl to more easily distinguish the two conditions.

The output is a serie of html files that contain information about the fastq files. For instance, the summary of the first control sample is shown here:

There are some sections that are flagged in red, but the samples might still be acceptable, also considering that crucial sections like the per base sequence quality, the per sequence quality scores, the per sequence GC content all have a good quality and typical behaviours.

The per base sequence quality represents the quality scores over the position in the reads. In my case the reads are 150 base pair long, as mentioned before, and I can see that in the first bases there is not high accuracy. That is completely normal, and indeed soon there is a calibration and the accuracy becomes higher, and then decreases again towards the end (which is again typical).

The Per Base Sequence content is flagged in red in all the reports, but I see that in approximately the first 10 base pairs the sequence content is unstable, but then it stabilises, which is quite normal for this type of data.

The per sequence GC content is flagged in red in the filaminB knocked-down samples, but still the shape of the distribution is quite close to the gaussian; there is not a binary distribution, but simply some smaller hills along the normal distribution:

As for the overrepresented sequences, we have an orange tag, which would indicate a reasonable quality. This section is useful for pinpoint possible contaminations or an excessive presence of adapters or primers that were added during the sequencing.

Many of the overepresented sequences (but often those with a lower presence) have not been recognised by the fastqc analysis, and I decide to try out a BLAST search as well for a sample of these fragments (whose sequence is specified by fastqc itself). I found that for instance some of the sequences might correspond with a >93% accuracy to synthetic cloning vectors.

Trimming with Trimmomatic¶

The quality of the files seems to be good enough; however I think that the percentage for the presence of overrepresented sequences could be lower, and additionally I know that during the analysis in the reference literature a trimming has been performed. Therefore I decide to trim the adapters from the fastqfiles, and I do so by using trimmomatic, which I have manually uploaded as zip file to the folder in its 0.36 version (after a first attempt with wget).

With Trimmomatic I perform a paired end (PE) trimming; the phred33 refers to the Sanger format that is used for sequencing starting from Illumina 1.8 and that should therefore be applied in this case as well. The trimming tool requires the forward and backward fastq files as input and will output four files, for the unparied and the paired reads. It will be enough for us to use the paired reads for subsequent mapping. The ILLUMINACLIP option is for the trimming of the adapters, whose reference sequences for alignment and comparison are provided with the tool itself (adapters/PE/TruSeq3). The rest of the options are quite standard and suggested by the tool provider itself for a soft quality trimming:

  • Remove leading low quality or N bases below quality 3 (LEADING:3)
  • Remove trailing low quality or N bases below quality 3 (TRAILING:3)
  • Scan the read with a 4-base wide sliding window, cutting when the average quality per base drops below 15 (SLIDINGWINDOW:4:15)
  • Drop reads below the 36 bases long (MINLEN:36)

Even though even after trimming some overrepresented sequences are still present, their presence has been significantly reduced by the trimming and is no higher than 0,5%; I have excluded that some of these might be caused by a specific contamination by BLASTing some of the overrepresented sequences and finding that they did not correspond to e.g. all to some other specific organism. The relevant sections of the fastqc analysis still show good results, and therefore I decide to proceed with the mapping and the analysis and accepting the samples.

In the trimmed quality analysis, we see an additional orange tag for the sequence lenght distribution given by the fact that we have performed the trimming, and therefore we do not have the classical tringle-shaped distribution that we previously had for the untrimmed reads.

Mapping to the genome with STAR¶

The mapping has been performed first on the untrimmed fastq files for comparison, but then the alignment for the trimmed files has been then used for further analyses (this is because I first had decided not to perform trimming on the files and carried out subsequent analyses on the untrimmed files, but later decided to go back and perform better tuning on the alignment).

The inspection of the bam files with flagstat and idxstat do not seem to reveal any problems in the alignment. These bam files can be visualised in IGV, and some of the relevant genes can be shown. Above is the control 1 sample (in blue) and below the Filamin B knockdown sample 1 (in red); the scaling has been set to equal values in order to be comparable.

The gene MALAT1 is a gene that is differentially expressed in the two conditions and that is associated with cancers like leukemia (Metastasis Associated Lung Adenocarcinoma Transcript 1).

NAIP on chromosome 5 is a low expressed gene whose expression is increased in the Filamin B knocked down (Neuronal Apoptosis Inhibitory Protein); it is one of the target genes more relevant in the reference literature, as its overexpression in the second condition is in line with the initial hypothesis of the study.

MMP13, which is fundamental for skeletal development, on chromosome 11 is not expressed in the control, and expressed in the filamin knockdown.

The file that we have created contains the read counts for all the genes in our dataset. For example, we see that for some of the genes of our interest these are the values that we obtain for each of the four samples (control 1, control 2, flnb knockdown 1 and flnb knockdown 2 respectively). I will analyse statistically this file in the next part of the assignment; notice that genes line NAIP and MMP13 will be selected out by DESeq2, that has a strict approach on lowly expressed genes (because they would otherwise hinder the statistical significance of the differential expression analysis). Nevertheless, I think it is still reliable to affirm that the filamin B knockdown presents an upregulation for these genes, even though the value of it is not assessable with DESeq2.
